<main>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
     HOME
══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="tab-home" class="tab-panel active">

  <div class="hero">
    <h1>A Public Facility. Private Control. No Accountability.</h1>
    <p>White Rock Boathouse sits on public land at White Rock Lake — owned by the City of Dallas and funded by every Dallas taxpayer. It is <strong>one of the largest boathouses in the country</strong>. Yet Dallas residents and nonprofit organizations are being turned away while two private schools and a private university are granted access as paying tenants. Financial safeguards mandated by City Council have gone <strong>unenforced</strong>, and the governing board has <strong>operated without oversight</strong>. The City has been informed at every step. It has chosen not to act.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="eyebrow">Three Documented Failures</div>
  <h2>What This Site Is About</h2>
  <div class="three-grid">
    <div class="three-card">
      <div class="icon">🚫</div>
      <span class="tag tag-red">Issue 1</span>
      <h3>Public Access Denied</h3>
      <p>Dallas residents and nonprofits are being turned away from a publicly-owned facility. The operator's Code of Conduct bans participation by anyone affiliated with a competing organization — on public property, using public resources.</p>
      <p style="margin-top:12px"><a href="#" onclick="show('issue1',document.querySelectorAll('nav button')[1]);return false;" style="color:var(--blue);font-weight:600;font-size:.88rem;">Read Issue 1 →</a></p>
    </div>
    <div class="three-card">
      <div class="icon">🏛️</div>
      <span class="tag tag-yellow">Issue 2</span>
      <h3>Unchecked Governance</h3>
      <p>A small, self-perpetuating private board has exercised long-term control over this city facility with no term limits — despite assurances made to the Park Board in 2019 that governance safeguards would be implemented.</p>
      <p style="margin-top:12px"><a href="#" onclick="show('issue2',document.querySelectorAll('nav button')[2]);return false;" style="color:var(--blue);font-weight:600;font-size:.88rem;">Read Issue 2 →</a></p>
    </div>
    <div class="three-card">
      <div class="icon">📋</div>
      <span class="tag tag-blue">Issue 3</span>
      <h3>Audit Mandate Unmet</h3>
      <p>A 2019 City audit found serious deficiencies. A 2022 contract amendment required independent financial audits. The operator has continued submitting weaker compilation reports — and the City has not enforced compliance.</p>
      <p style="margin-top:12px"><a href="#" onclick="show('issue3',document.querySelectorAll('nav button')[3]);return false;" style="color:var(--blue);font-weight:600;font-size:.88rem;">Read Issue 3 →</a></p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-red">
    <strong>⚠ City Staff Have Acknowledged the Problem — And Done Nothing</strong>
    <p>According to documented accounts, City staff have acknowledged that certain practices at the boathouse are <em>"not right, or against Texas law"</em> — yet the City's official response has been to say the contract is with the operator, and that public access is simply not the City's concern. A <strong>citizen-prepared briefing submitted to Dallas City Council on February 8, 2026</strong> — drawing on public records, open records disclosures, and documented City communications — lays out all three issues in detail.</p>
  </div>

</div><!-- /home -->


<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
     ISSUE 1: ACCESS
══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="tab-issue1" class="tab-panel">

  <div class="issue-header">
    <div class="issue-num">1</div>
    <div class="issue-header-text">
      <div class="eyebrow">Issue 1 of 3 &middot; Citizen Briefing to City Council, Feb. 8, 2026</div>
      <h2>Public Access &amp; Use of a City Asset</h2>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card top-blue">
    <span class="tag tag-red">Privatization of Public Property</span>
    <p>White Rock Boathouse is a <strong>city-owned facility on public land</strong> — and one of the <strong>largest boathouses in the country</strong>. Its founding agreement states it exists "for the use and enjoyment to all segments of the Dallas Community." Yet citizens and nonprofit rowing programs report being routinely <strong>excluded and restricted</strong> from this expansive, taxpayer-funded facility.</p>
    <p>Signage at or near the building and docks reportedly indicates <strong>"private" property</strong> — on land owned by the City of Dallas and maintained with public funds.</p>
    <p>Access restrictions have been justified by the operator on <strong>"capacity" grounds</strong>. However, City emails obtained through open records requests indicate that capacity is, in fact, available. <strong>No independent, City-reviewed capacity assessment has ever been conducted.</strong></p>
    <p>Meanwhile, <strong>three private programs operate inside the city-owned building as paying tenants</strong> — at non-publicly disclosed rental rates negotiated with the operator alone, with no City review:</p>
  </div>

  <!-- WHO GETS IN vs. WHO DOESN'T -->
  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:20px;margin:22px 0 28px;">
    <div class="card" style="border-top:4px solid var(--red);">
      <span class="tag tag-red">Turned Away</span>
      <h3>Dallas Community &amp; Nonprofits</h3>
      <p>Dallas residents, independent rowers, and nonprofit rowing organizations affiliated with any organization that competes with the operator are denied access — on publicly-owned land, in a publicly-funded facility.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="border-top:4px solid #4a7c3f;">
      <span class="tag" style="background:#e8f5e9;color:#2e5c28;border:1px solid #a8d5a2;">Granted Access</span>
      <h3>Three Private Programs</h3>
      <p>The following programs operate as tenants inside the City-owned building, paying rent to the private operator at undisclosed rates:</p>
      <ul style="margin-top:10px;padding-left:18px;font-size:.9rem;color:var(--gray);line-height:1.9;">
        <li><strong>Jesuit College Preparatory School</strong> — a private school in Dallas</li>
        <li><strong>Ursuline Academy of Dallas</strong> — a private school in Dallas</li>
        <li><strong>Southern Methodist University (SMU) Women's Rowing Team</strong> — a private university located in Highland Park, a separate municipality outside the City of Dallas</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-gold">
    <strong>The Double Standard in Plain Terms</strong>
    <p>Two private schools and a private university — none of them City of Dallas public institutions — have been granted tenancy inside a <em>City-owned public facility</em>, paying rent to a private operator whose rates are not publicly disclosed. At the same time, Dallas community members and nonprofit rowing organizations are turned away. The City of Dallas has taken no action to investigate or change this arrangement.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-red">
    <strong>Citizen Briefing Finding</strong>
    <p>A City asset may be operating in a way that <strong>effectively privatizes access</strong>, presents public land and docks as private property, and embeds undisclosed private tenancy in a public facility — all without City oversight or review.</p>
  </div>

  <hr class="divider"/>

  <!-- Code of Conduct -->
  <div class="eyebrow">Supporting Evidence</div>
  <h2>The Code of Conduct: How Access Is Restricted</h2>

  <div class="card top-red">
    <span class="tag tag-red">Code of Conduct Analysis · 2018–2024</span>
    <h3>From Community Policy to Exclusion Tool</h3>
    <p>A review of White Rock Boathouse's Codes of Conduct from 2018 through 2024 reveals a systematic shift away from public access toward exclusionary, private-club-style control:</p>
    <p><strong>City oversight removed:</strong> The 2021 version included a City oversight and reporting pathway for resolving disputes. By 2023, this was removed entirely — meaning WRBH now enforces its own membership bans without any City review, potentially violating the terms of a public facility lease.</p>
    <p><strong>Anti-competition clauses introduced:</strong> Starting in 2021, the Code began requiring mandatory affiliation and restricting members from volunteering or coaching at other clubs. These rules appear designed to <strong>exclude community participation</strong> and suppress competition — on publicly-owned property.</p>
    <p><strong>Due process eliminated:</strong> The 2018 version gave members the right to defend themselves before termination. This protection was eliminated by 2023.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-red">
    <strong>Why This Matters</strong>
    <p>Restricting access to a city-managed public facility based on external affiliations may conflict with public-access and equal-opportunity provisions under municipal and civil-rights law. The City has been made aware of these Code changes — and has taken no action to review or reverse them.</p>
  </div>

  <hr class="divider"/>

  <!-- City Email on Access -->
  <div class="eyebrow">The City's Official Response</div>
  <h2>What the City Said When Asked About Public Access</h2>
  <p style="color:var(--gray);margin-bottom:18px;font-size:.95rem;">When concerned residents raised the issue of public access denials, this is the official written response from the City of Dallas Park &amp; Recreation Superintendent:</p>

  <div class="evidence-label">📧 City Email — Obtained via Open Records</div>
  <div class="email-wrap">
    <div class="email-head">
      <div class="email-from">From: Olusola (Shola) Adebajo — Superintendent, Dallas Park &amp; Recreation</div>
      <div class="email-meta">
        <strong>To:</strong> Austin, Maryann &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Cc:</strong> Clyde<br/>
        <strong>Subject:</strong> RE: Question of Public Access
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="email-body">
      <p>Good Morning Austin,</p>
      <p>I appreciate your concern and need for clarity as it relates to contractual terms and obligations. <strong>There is nothing within White Rock Boathouse, Inc.'s contract that prohibits them from denying individuals affiliated with another rowing organization that competes with the one sponsored by White Rock Boathouse, Inc. access to the premises.</strong> Furthermore, there is nothing that prohibits them from denying access to any individual/organization from the premises period.</p>
      <p>The City of Dallas is not a party to any agreement White Rock Boathouse, Inc. has with any independent rowing organizations nor are we privy to what those requirements for access are. <strong>The City's contract is with White Rock Boathouse Inc. solely and we are only responsible for enforcing that contract.</strong></p>
      <p>Yours Sincerely,</p>
      <div class="email-sig">
        <strong>Shola Adebajo</strong><br/>
        Superintendent, Park &amp; Recreation Department<br/>
        City of Dallas &nbsp;|&nbsp; Office: 214-670-8858
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-gold">
    <strong>What This Email Tells Us</strong>
    <p>The City Superintendent openly admits the City's own contract contains <strong>no requirement that this public facility remain open to the public</strong>. The operator can deny access to anyone — and the City considers this acceptable. The City claims it has no responsibility for ensuring that a taxpayer-funded facility on public land serves the public. This is the official position of the City of Dallas.</p>
  </div>

</div><!-- /issue1 -->


<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
     ISSUE 2: GOVERNANCE
══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="tab-issue2" class="tab-panel">

  <div class="issue-header">
    <div class="issue-num">2</div>
    <div class="issue-header-text">
      <div class="eyebrow">Issue 2 of 3 &middot; Citizen Briefing to City Council, Feb. 8, 2026</div>
      <h2>Governance Practices of the Operator</h2>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card top-blue">
    <span class="tag tag-yellow">Private Club Control Over Public Facility</span>
    <p>The operator, White Rock Boathouse, Inc., appears to use <strong>private-club-style discretion</strong> over who may participate in and access the facility — including selective admission, re-admission criteria, and codes of conduct that dictate who can participate and under what conditions.</p>
    <p>The operator's board operates with <strong>no term limits</strong>, enabling long-term concentration of control over the management of a city asset. A small group of individuals has exercised ongoing, unchecked authority over a publicly-owned facility without standard nonprofit governance safeguards.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-red">
    <strong>Promises Made to the Park Board in 2019 — Never Kept</strong>
    <p>In the September 5, 2019 Park Board meeting, the operator reportedly assured the Park Board that <strong>term limits and other governance safeguards would be implemented</strong>. Those commitments were never fulfilled. After some initial adjustments following City engagement, practices reverted — suggesting either weak follow-through by City staff or deliberate non-compliance by the operator.</p>
  </div>

  <hr class="divider"/>

  <div class="eyebrow">Why This Matters</div>
  <h2>The Governance Failure in Plain Terms</h2>

  <div class="card">
    <h3>No Term Limits = No Accountability</h3>
    <p>When the same individuals control a private nonprofit board indefinitely, there is no mechanism for fresh perspectives, community input, or corrective change. For a board operating a <strong>city-owned public facility</strong>, this is not just a governance concern — it raises serious questions about whose interests are being served.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <h3>The City Has the Authority — But Has Not Used It</h3>
    <p>The City of Dallas is the landlord of this facility and a party to the operating contract. It has the legal authority to require governance standards as a condition of the lease. It has not done so, despite repeated concerns raised by the public, Park Board members, and documented instances of the operator reverting to prior practices.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <h3>Self-Policing Without City Review</h3>
    <p>As documented in the Code of Conduct analysis (see Issue 1), the operator removed the City oversight pathway from its governing documents by 2023. The board now enforces its own membership bans, exclusions, and conduct rules — on a public facility — with no City review process in place.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-gold">
    <strong>Citizen Briefing Finding</strong>
    <p>A small, self-perpetuating private board appears to exercise long-term control over a city facility, <strong>without clear evidence of standard governance safeguards being in place or enforced</strong> — despite prior assurances and a documented history of noncompliance.</p>
  </div>

