<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
     ISSUE 3: AUDIT FAILURES
══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="tab-issue3" class="tab-panel">

  <div class="issue-header">
    <div class="issue-num">3</div>
    <div class="issue-header-text">
      <div class="eyebrow">Issue 3 of 3 &middot; Citizen Briefing to City Council, Feb. 8, 2026</div>
      <h2>Financial Accountability &amp; Audit Failures</h2>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p style="color:var(--gray);font-size:.97rem;margin-bottom:28px;">This issue has a documented paper trail. A City audit found problems. The City created a legal obligation to fix them. The operator has not complied. The City has not enforced. Here is the full story:</p>

  <!-- Step flow -->
  <div class="eyebrow">The Audit Trail — Step by Step</div>
  <h2>How We Got Here</h2>

  <div class="step-flow">

    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-line">
        <div class="step-dot">1</div>
        <div class="step-connector"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <div class="step-date">2019 — City Audit Report A19-010</div>
        <h3>Audit Finds Serious Deficiencies at White Rock Boathouse</h3>
        <p>Called for by City Council Member Mark Clayton, the 2019 City audit found that the Park &amp; Recreation Division had <strong>no formal policies or procedures</strong> for contract oversight of White Rock Boathouse. Key findings included:</p>
        <p>• The Boathouse operated the Boomerang Boathouse under an <strong>expired contract</strong> from mid-2013 to late 2018 — and the City failed to notice.</p>
        <p>• The City never validated whether the revenue figures used to calculate payments were accurate or complete.</p>
        <p>• Prior to November 2016, Boathouse did not maintain <strong>identifiable financial records</strong>.</p>
        <p>• From FY 2013–2017, Boathouse did not submit required annual financial statements in accordance with GAAP.</p>
        <p>• <strong>Boathouse did not have adequate internal controls over expenses.</strong></p>
        <p>The audit concluded that the City could not confirm whether required payments were complete or accurate, and that the risk of undetected contract noncompliance was high.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-line">
        <div class="step-dot">2</div>
        <div class="step-connector"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <div class="step-date">March 2022 — Supplemental Agreement No. 1</div>
        <h3>City Requires Independent Audits — In Writing, By Contract</h3>
        <p>In direct response to the 2019 audit findings, the City and White Rock Boathouse executed a formal contract amendment — <strong>Supplemental Agreement No. 1</strong> (City File No. 22-5339, effective February 10, 2022).</p>
        <p>Section 8.15 of the amended agreement explicitly requires that Boathouse's year-end financial information be either:</p>
        <p><strong>(a)</strong> Audited by an independent certified public accountant; <em>or</em></p>
        <p><strong>(b)</strong> Examined by an independent CPA with an <em>Examination-Level Attestation Report</em> — which requires the CPA to express an opinion and provide assurance that Filter Building gross sales and revenues are materially complete and accurate, and that Boathouse is conducting proper accounting and internal controls.</p>
        <p>This was not a suggestion. It was a <strong>contractual obligation</strong>, signed by the City Manager and the Boathouse President.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-line">
        <div class="step-dot warn">3</div>
        <div class="step-connector"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <div class="step-date">2022–2024 — Non-Compliance</div>
        <h3>Operator Submits Compilations — Not Audits — And the City Does Nothing</h3>
        <p>Despite the clear contractual requirement, financial submissions for fiscal years <strong>2022 and 2024</strong> were provided via <em>Compilation Reports</em>. A compilation is a fundamentally different — and significantly weaker — form of financial reporting:</p>
        <p>• A <strong>compilation</strong> involves no testing, no verification, and no independent assurance. It merely organizes management-provided numbers into financial statement format.</p>
        <p>• An <strong>audit or examination with attestation</strong> requires the CPA to independently verify the accuracy of revenue figures and provide a professional opinion.</p>
        <p>The CPA reports on file <strong>do not reflect independent verification of gross revenue figures</strong> used to calculate payments owed to the City. Based on unverified submissions, the City received $38,431 (2022) and $25,365 (2024).</p>
        <p><strong>No City department has been identified as responsible for verifying or enforcing the audit requirement.</strong></p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-line">
        <div class="step-dot warn">!</div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <div class="step-date">Today — The Enforcement Gap</div>
        <h3>A Council-Level Safeguard, Completely Unenforced</h3>
        <p>The City Council mandated independent financial oversight after the 2019 audit revealed that the City could not verify whether it was receiving the correct payments from the Boathouse. That mandate is now itself unenforced. <strong>The problem the audit was meant to fix has not been fixed.</strong></p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div><!-- /step-flow -->

  <!-- City email on audit -->
  <hr class="divider"/>
  <div class="eyebrow">Supporting Evidence</div>
  <h2>The City's Own Email Confirms Non-Compliance Was Known</h2>
  <p style="color:var(--gray);font-size:.94rem;margin-bottom:18px;">On January 28, 2025, Nicole Oliver, Supervisor of Business for the Dallas Park &amp; Recreation Department, sent the following email to the White Rock Boathouse operator — acknowledging that the 2023 year-end financial report <strong>did not meet the Supplemental Agreement requirements</strong>:</p>

  <div class="evidence-label">📧 City Email — Obtained via Open Records</div>
  <div class="email-wrap">
    <div class="email-head">
      <div class="email-from">From: Nicole Oliver — Supervisor, Business, Dallas Park &amp; Recreation</div>
      <div class="email-meta">
        <strong>To:</strong> Sue Ellen Chambers, White Rock Rowing &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Cc:</strong> Hernandez, Maryann<br/>
        <strong>Date:</strong> Tuesday, January 28, 2025, 2:01 PM<br/>
        <strong>Subject:</strong> WRBI – Year End Financials Requirement for 2024
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="email-body">
      <p>Sue Ellen,</p>
      <p>Our internal controls manager reviewed your 2023 Year-end Financial Reports and noticed that <strong>the report did not meet the Supplement #1 requirements.</strong> While the report was prepared in GAAP, it was not audited by an independent certified public accountant OR examined by an independent CPA that provided an Examination-Level Attestation Report. That report requires the CPA to provide an opinion and assure that the Filter Building Gross Sales and Revenues are accurate. You can choose either option.</p>
      <p>For your 2024 year end financials, please make sure they are either audited or if providing the attestation report they state an opinion.</p>
      <p>If you have any questions about this just let me know.</p>
      <p>Thanks,</p>
      <div class="email-sig">
        <strong>Nicole Oliver</strong><br/>
        Supervisor – Business, City of Dallas | dallasparks.org<br/>
        Dallas Park and Recreation Department<br/>
        5620 Parkdale, Dallas, Texas 75227<br/>
        O: 214.670.8568 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <a href="mailto:Nicole.Oliver@dallas.gov">Nicole.Oliver@dallas.gov</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-gold">
    <strong>What This Email Confirms</strong>
    <p>The City's own internal controls manager identified in January 2025 that the 2023 financial report <strong>did not meet Supplemental Agreement No. 1 requirements</strong>. This is not an outside claim — it is the City's own finding, in writing. The email asks the operator to fix this for 2024. Whether the 2024 submission meets requirements remains in question, and <strong>no enforcement action has been taken for the prior year's non-compliant submission.</strong></p>
  </div>

  <!-- Operator Response (from second screenshot) -->
  <div class="callout callout-blue">
    <strong>The Operator's Response</strong>
    <p>In reply to the City's January 2025 email, White Rock Boathouse's Sue Ellen Chambers responded: <em>"I have sent your email to the CPA we use to provide our attestation report. He dealt directly with the city during the audit for an agreed-upon acceptable audit process and will be able to address this matter."</em></p>
    <p>The operator did not commit to providing a compliant report — they referred the matter back to a CPA who had previously provided non-compliant submissions. As of the February 8, 2026 citizen briefing, <strong>no compliant independent audit for fiscal year 2022 or 2024 has been identified.</strong></p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-red">
    <strong>Citizen Briefing Finding</strong>
    <p>A Council-level safeguard — independent audits required after prior deficiencies were identified — may be unmet and unenforced. <strong>It is unclear which City department or position is responsible for verifying and enforcing this audit requirement.</strong> The City does not currently have independent confirmation of the gross revenue figures that determine how much the operator owes the public.</p>
  </div>

</div><!-- /issue3 -->


